00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:42.860
But now within the
last six months,

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:45.790
I moved out to Northern
California based out of there.

00:01:45.790 --> 00:01:47.610
FEMALE SPEAKER: So
what brought you

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:49.780
from doing photography
for "National

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:52.164
Geographic" to filmmaking?

00:01:52.164 --> 00:01:53.580
LOUIE PSIHOYOS: A
friend of mine--

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.430
this will be probably be
interesting to the tech people

00:01:55.430 --> 00:01:55.929
here.

00:01:55.929 --> 00:02:00.100
But a good friend of mine
that was my dive buddy

00:02:00.100 --> 00:02:02.520
was Jim Clark, the guy
that started Netscape,

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.410
Silicon Graphics, WebMD.

00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:07.080
Netscape was the first
commercial internet browser.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:09.070
I photographed him for
"Fortune Magazine."

00:02:09.070 --> 00:02:11.140
I used to be a photographer
in a former life.

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:13.350
And I photographed
him when he built

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:16.190
this big boat called Hyperion
that had the world's tallest

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:16.690
mast.

00:02:16.690 --> 00:02:18.664
And we were hanging
out in Amsterdam.

00:02:18.664 --> 00:02:19.830
His boat was being launched.

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:21.767
And we found out we
both liked to dive.

00:02:21.767 --> 00:02:23.350
And he said, Louie,
would you teach me

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:24.400
how to be a good photographer?

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:26.140
And I said, Jim, I'll teach
you how to be a great one

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.080
if you teach me how
to be a billionaire.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.750
And so he would pick
me up on his plane.

00:02:30.750 --> 00:02:33.250
And we would go around
the world and go

00:02:33.250 --> 00:02:34.740
to some of the
most amazing places

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:37.890
in the world-- places I could
never have done on my own.

00:02:37.890 --> 00:02:40.290
And I taught him photography.

00:02:40.290 --> 00:02:41.320
We just explored.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:44.410
And this was the third time
we were in the Galapagos.

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:47.080
And there was fisherman
illegally long

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:49.931
lining in a marine
sanctuary all around us and.

00:02:49.931 --> 00:02:52.180
And Jim said, somebody should
do something about this.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:54.465
And I said, how about you and I?

00:02:54.465 --> 00:02:55.940
And he said, what do you mean?

00:02:55.940 --> 00:02:58.275
I said, we'll use your
money, and my eye,

00:02:58.275 --> 00:02:59.750
and we'll make films.

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:01.800
And I thought that
was-- to me, I always

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:02.850
wanted to be a filmmaker.

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:03.940
I'd worked for
"National Geographic"

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:04.940
as a still photographer.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:07.540
But it wasn't my
area of expertise.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:10.542
And so he was going to fund
me for about a million dollars

00:03:10.542 --> 00:03:12.250
a year, which is a
hefty amount of money.

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:15.600
It was a good amount of money
for a documentary filmmaker.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.930
But I've never made a
film before in my life.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:21.220
And so now, we were on vacation
together down in the Caribbean.

00:03:21.220 --> 00:03:22.770
And my kid is
playing on the beach

00:03:22.770 --> 00:03:26.300
with another kid whose father
is a pretty well-known film

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:27.580
director.

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:29.620
And Steven Spielberg
comes over to the boat

00:03:29.620 --> 00:03:33.650
and says, I said to
him, Mr. Spielberg,

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:36.250
do you have any advice for
a first-time filmmaker?

00:03:36.250 --> 00:03:40.592
He said, yeah never make a movie
involving any boats or animals.

00:03:40.592 --> 00:03:42.300
Now, the first film
I did was "The Cove,"

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.690
which became the most winning
documentary in history.

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:47.785
It won over 70 top film
awards from Sundance

00:03:47.785 --> 00:03:50.040
to the Academy Award.

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:51.770
But that was our first film.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:55.965
But the idea was-- did
people here see "The Cove"?

00:03:55.965 --> 00:03:56.909
A couple?

00:03:56.909 --> 00:03:58.200
Yeah, so about half the people.

00:03:58.200 --> 00:03:59.616
Another half
probably heard of it,

00:03:59.616 --> 00:04:01.940
or they're scared to
see it, because it

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.620
has the stigma of being
a really violent film.

00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:06.610
And it has one
section in it that is

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:09.440
pretty-- it is hard to watch.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:11.250
It was hard for me to make.

00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:13.230
We had planted hidden
cameras in this place

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:15.730
where they killed more dolphins
than any place in the world.

00:04:15.730 --> 00:04:20.029
This is where they supply--
this place in Taiji, Japan--

00:04:20.029 --> 00:04:24.480
they kill several
thousand dolphins a year.

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:27.300
And the ones that are
looking for young females

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:31.070
that they put into service in
the captive dolphin industry.

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:33.900
Most of them swim with dolphin
parks in Asia and Europe

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:37.450
and come out of this
one little cove.

00:04:37.450 --> 00:04:39.810
And we saw how do they
kill these animals?

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:40.910
What do they do with them?

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:42.250
We planted these hidden cameras.

00:04:42.250 --> 00:04:46.230
And it' sort of became
like a James Bond movie.

00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:48.360
The whole film
took a turn when we

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:49.880
decide to sneak into this cove.

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:51.150
And it became really exciting.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:52.691
It wasn't just a
documentary anymore.

00:04:52.691 --> 00:04:55.982
It was like-- I think
"Rolling Stone" called

00:04:55.982 --> 00:04:57.940
the movie a cross between
the "Bourne Identity"

00:04:57.940 --> 00:04:59.400
and "Flipper."

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.236
And it was exciting.

00:05:01.236 --> 00:05:03.360
We had some amazing footage
that came out of there.

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:05.330
But here's the really
cool thing about the film

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:07.940
aside from all
the awards that we

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:10.980
got from doing that one film is
that they were killing 23,000

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.590
dolphins and porpoises
a year in Japan

00:05:12.590 --> 00:05:13.714
when we started that movie.

00:05:13.714 --> 00:05:15.820
Now, they are killing
less than 6,000

00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:18.830
mostly because of that
movie, because in the movie,

00:05:18.830 --> 00:05:20.810
we explain that
how they're killed.

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:24.090
And we also explain that
these animals are toxic.

00:05:24.090 --> 00:05:27.090
A dolphin today,
because of the ocean

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:30.929
is so polluted by what we
put into it-- for those

00:05:30.929 --> 00:05:33.470
who haven't seen the movie or
don't remember the movie if you

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:35.690
saw it-- there are
six levels of the food

00:05:35.690 --> 00:05:39.240
chain in the ocean from
plankton up to dolphins.

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:41.650
And at every tropic level,
each of those trophic levels

00:05:41.650 --> 00:05:43.810
is an order of magnitude
more pollution.

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:47.590
So a pound of swordfish or
a pound of dolphin flesh

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:49.940
has a million times
more pollutants in it

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:51.700
than a pound of
plankton, because it all

00:05:51.700 --> 00:05:54.240
gets magnified up
the food chain,

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:57.080
to the point where
a dolphin washing up

00:05:57.080 --> 00:06:00.170
on the coast of New
York state right now

00:06:00.170 --> 00:06:07.680
has about 6,000 parts
of PCBs in them.

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:11.300
That would be eligible
for a Superfund site--

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:13.510
just that one dolphin.

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:15.590
And now people in
Japan are eating this.

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:18.327
So just by giving them the
information that the government

00:06:18.327 --> 00:06:20.910
wasn't giving them, because you
go to the Minister of Health's

00:06:20.910 --> 00:06:24.960
website in Japan, they
had advisories for women

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:27.840
to be eating dolphin meat,
even thought it's toxic.

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:31.940
One piece of toxic
dolphin meat could

00:06:31.940 --> 00:06:34.630
be enough to maybe
make your fetus abort.

00:06:34.630 --> 00:06:38.540
And so now those numbers
dropped precipitously.

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:41.090
And I'll just steamroll
right into the next idea.

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:45.490
So I'm at Sundance with
"The Cove" as our premier.

00:06:45.490 --> 00:06:47.044
And my own background
is that when

00:06:47.044 --> 00:06:48.460
I worked at National
Geographic, I

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:50.930
did stories on the Mesozoic--
the mid-life of the planet--

00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:54.320
this is the age of dinosaurs--
and dug up dinosaurs

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:55.320
all around the world.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:57.970
I did a book on dinosaurs
called "Hunting Dinosaurs."

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:00.969
And I used basically 50
of the top paleontologist

00:07:00.969 --> 00:07:03.010
in the world as tour guides
through the Mesozoic.

00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:04.790
So I know a bit
about this subject.

00:07:04.790 --> 00:07:07.480
I spent 10 years
working in that world.

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:10.974
But at Sundance, I
brought a book with me--

00:07:10.974 --> 00:07:13.390
it was called "Terra" by Michael
Novacek, the head provost

00:07:13.390 --> 00:07:16.750
American Museum of Natural
History at 81st and Columbus.

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:19.250
And in the book, he's talking
about how we're losing species

00:07:19.250 --> 00:07:20.920
now faster than
mankind's ability

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:23.700
to record these animals are
even on the planet with us.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:25.627
And I thought, this is horrific.

00:07:25.627 --> 00:07:27.460
And I didn't want--
that's not the headspace

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:27.990
I wanted to be in.

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:29.330
I wanted to show them
the premier of my film.

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:31.413
So I picked the only other
book I brought with me.

00:07:31.413 --> 00:07:34.910
But this was by Charles Veron,
former chief marine scientist

00:07:34.910 --> 00:07:35.950
for Australia.

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:37.560
In the book he is talking about
we're losing the Great Barrier

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:39.420
Reef now and all other
reefs on the planet because

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:40.200
of acidification.

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:42.980
That's exactly what goes on
before a mass extinction event.

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:44.110
That's what we're going
through right now.

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:46.270
And I thought here I am running
this organization called

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:47.780
the Oceanic
Preservation Society.

00:07:47.780 --> 00:07:50.380
I consider myself a lay
expert in this field.

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:53.290
And I had no idea that we were
losing the oceans that quick.

00:07:53.290 --> 00:07:55.970
I had no idea we were in the
middle of what scientists

00:07:55.970 --> 00:07:58.400
are calling the
Anthropocene-- the age of man.

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:02.360
This is an epoch
where we are leaving

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:04.930
a mark on the fossil record
of the future to the point

00:08:04.930 --> 00:08:08.654
that future generations can see
that there's a line we arrived.

00:08:08.654 --> 00:08:10.070
They're probably
not going to be--

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:12.670
they'll be looking at the
computers in the garbage dump.

00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:15.320
And they're going to see--
it will be like an iridium

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:17.740
layer-- you know,
when the comet hit

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:20.329
the dinosaurs 65
million years ago,

00:08:20.329 --> 00:08:21.870
it wiped out all
the large dinosaurs.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:23.340
It was left with
an iridium layer.

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:28.536
There's not dinosaurs
above that iridium layer.

00:08:28.536 --> 00:08:29.910
But there's a
dinosaurs below it.

00:08:29.910 --> 00:08:33.549
So we know that there
was a catastrophic event.

00:08:33.549 --> 00:08:35.570
When future
generations look back

00:08:35.570 --> 00:08:37.960
at our plume of
the iridium layer,

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:40.210
they're going to
see our garbage.

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:43.380
And I think that if we don't
do a great job at trying

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:45.494
to mitigate this
problem, we're not

00:08:45.494 --> 00:08:47.660
going to looking to say how
great our computers are,

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:49.790
how great our technology
is, how wonderful it

00:08:49.790 --> 00:08:51.390
is that we can communicate
at the speed of light

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:52.139
across the planet.

00:08:52.139 --> 00:08:57.210
They're going to say that
this generation presided

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.600
over the biggest
apocalypse on the planet

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:03.050
since the dinosaurs were
wiped out by a comet

00:09:03.050 --> 00:09:04.840
65 million years ago.

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:06.570
So it just shocked
me at Sundance

00:09:06.570 --> 00:09:09.690
to realize that we were in
the middle of this epoch

00:09:09.690 --> 00:09:12.020
that I was oblivious
to, because when

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:13.914
you're digging dinosaurs
around the planet,

00:09:13.914 --> 00:09:16.330
you're looking around at these
graveyards like in the Gobi

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.130
Desert with Michael Novacek.

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:20.200
And you almost trip
over dinosaurs.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:21.700
You think, what happened here?

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:22.990
What went on?

00:09:22.990 --> 00:09:26.560
And it's sandstorms and
all this cataclysmic stuff.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:30.000
In the iridium layer, it's
pretty easy to spot it.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:31.910
But to think that
we're going to an event

00:09:31.910 --> 00:09:34.770
like that right now, because
this is comfortable-- we're all

00:09:34.770 --> 00:09:35.869
having lunch.

00:09:35.869 --> 00:09:36.910
It's air conditioned air.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:39.080
We can communicate
on our phones,

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:43.420
and at the speed of light,
thoughts that we might have.

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:46.990
But it to the natural world,
to the rest of the planet,

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:48.559
we're just one species.

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:50.350
We don't even know by
an order of magnitude

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:51.976
how many animals
we're sharing it with.

00:09:51.976 --> 00:09:53.600
But we know we're
losing faster than we

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:54.890
can record that they're here.

00:09:54.890 --> 00:09:56.610
Some people say 8.5
million, 10 million.

00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:59.110
We've only identified about a
million and a half species out

00:09:59.110 --> 00:10:01.550
of the whole catalog of
maybe 8 million, 30 million,

00:10:01.550 --> 00:10:02.390
100 million species.

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:04.220
We don't even know.

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:07.390
So I look at things
because of hanging around

00:10:07.390 --> 00:10:10.000
with paleontologist, I look at
things a little bit different.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.510
They have an appreciation
of what's called deep time

00:10:12.510 --> 00:10:14.510
where the guys go
and dig up dinosaurs.

00:10:14.510 --> 00:10:17.020
But they're not looking
at-- they're not

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:19.349
thinking about-- they might
be thinking about lunch.

00:10:19.349 --> 00:10:21.140
But they're also thinking
about the animals

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:22.056
that they are digging.

00:10:22.056 --> 00:10:24.986
How do they fit into this
whole history of life?

00:10:24.986 --> 00:10:26.860
And now, as a photographer
and as a filmmaker

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:28.234
I'm trying to
think of how do you

00:10:28.234 --> 00:10:33.000
make a film about perhaps
the most cataclysmic event

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:34.800
in the world that
nobody knows about,

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:38.400
but give them a sense of
hope after they see the film.

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:39.970
There's something
that we can do.

00:10:39.970 --> 00:10:44.700
I don't want to just make a
film like a NOVA film, which

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:47.752
are really well produced,
but don't give you

00:10:47.752 --> 00:10:49.710
tangible ideas of what
you can do to change it,

00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:53.240
because this is a planetary
disaster on the scale that

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:54.610
is unprecedented.

00:10:54.610 --> 00:10:58.120
You can't be saying that
the house is burning down.

00:10:58.120 --> 00:11:01.120
You have to say, what can you do
to get buckets of water on it?

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:04.660
So that was "Racing Extinction."

00:11:04.660 --> 00:11:10.150
But the film-- when you do
it normal Hollywood film,

00:11:10.150 --> 00:11:14.310
they look at you, the audiences,
$10 and a box of popcorn.

00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:16.220
You're just butts in seats.

00:11:16.220 --> 00:11:20.410
And I don't look at documentary
filmmaking like that.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:22.860
I look at you as minds in
seats and more importantly,

00:11:22.860 --> 00:11:25.640
minds and hearts in
seats, because the science

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.130
shows that people don't
change behavior on what

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:32.530
they learn-- what they think.

00:11:32.530 --> 00:11:34.420
You have to change
their heart first.

00:11:34.420 --> 00:11:38.140
You can talk about 30,000
species dying every day.

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:39.670
And it's just a calculation.

00:11:39.670 --> 00:11:40.360
That's a number.

00:11:40.360 --> 00:11:42.109
It's a statistic.

00:11:42.109 --> 00:11:43.900
But early in the film,
"Racing Extinction,"

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:48.227
we show the scene--
and actually, you

00:11:48.227 --> 00:11:50.060
might want to direct
this a little bit more.

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:51.850
You can stop me
anytime you want.

00:11:51.850 --> 00:11:55.910
But at the beginning of this
film, I find a buoy on a beach.

00:11:55.910 --> 00:11:59.540
It was down in the
Dominican Republic.

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:03.640
And this fisherman had brought--
said you guys are from America.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:07.840
Can you give me $500 as
a reward for this buoy?

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:12.280
And I said, let me see
what this buoy looks like.

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:14.316
And it was a big
thing and not too

00:12:14.316 --> 00:12:15.690
easy to carry back
up to America.

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.010
But it was actually owned by
a friend of mine, Chris Clark

00:12:18.010 --> 00:12:19.759
from the Cornell
bioacoustical laboratory.

00:12:19.759 --> 00:12:24.250
He runs the biggest repository
of animal sounds on the planet

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:26.370
And after I returned
this buoy, he

00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:29.389
tells me, Louie, just about
everything on the planet's

00:12:29.389 --> 00:12:29.930
been singing.

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:30.860
We just haven't been listening.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:32.170
We're losing these voices.

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:35.260
He plays for me the
voice of an o'o.

00:12:35.260 --> 00:12:39.960
This is a bird from Kauai--
the small island of Kauai

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:41.380
in the Hawaiian Islands.

00:12:41.380 --> 00:12:46.040
And he tells me that
these birds mate for life.

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:50.020
And a dueting pair
where he'll sing.

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:52.510
Then she answers with a song.

00:12:52.510 --> 00:12:54.750
And it's a beautiful duet.

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:58.830
But he's only playing me
the male side of the duet.

00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:01.077
And there's a gap where
the female should be.

00:13:01.077 --> 00:13:02.160
And he says, you know why?

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.200
He says, that's the
last male of the species

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:07.420
singing for a female
that will never come.

00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:08.347
That breaks my heart.

00:13:08.347 --> 00:13:09.930
And it should break
everybody's heart,

00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:11.390
because you can identify.

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:15.080
It's no longer just one of the
30,000 species, some number.

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:18.580
It's like you can identify
with that one animal.

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:21.380
It's like the martian in
the film that came out.

00:13:21.380 --> 00:13:25.670
There's a whole film based on
one guy's trying to survive.

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:29.040
But you can imagine where
there's no hope for this bird.

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:33.020
Michael Novacek was
saying to me that after I

00:13:33.020 --> 00:13:34.950
came back and
interviewed him, he said,

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:37.230
he was doing a dissertation.

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:39.580
There was five grad students
doing their dissertations.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:42.120
And three of them were
doing dissertations

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:43.690
on the birds of Hawaii.

00:13:43.690 --> 00:13:45.880
I think five of the
birds went extinct

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:47.380
in the three-year
period that they

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:48.940
were working on the papers.

00:13:48.940 --> 00:13:51.400
That's how fast things
are disappearing.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:56.450
So to me, it's really crucial
to make a movie, to get it out

00:13:56.450 --> 00:13:59.600
there at light speed
so people can start

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:02.810
getting their heart changed,
because the solutions,

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:05.430
which we can talk about later,
are really fairly simple.

00:14:07.934 --> 00:14:10.470
There's five major
drivers of extinction

00:14:10.470 --> 00:14:13.440
is habitat destruction,
pollution, invasive species,

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:16.060
over-consumption-- just
that four-- I can't

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:17.260
remember the fifth one.

00:14:17.260 --> 00:14:19.420
We try to address
them all in the movie.

00:14:19.420 --> 00:14:26.420
But the idea is that the
biggest problem with extinction

00:14:26.420 --> 00:14:28.080
is habitat destruction.

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:31.240
And that's because we're
tearing down rain forests.

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:33.240
We're tearing down
natural habitat

00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:36.390
to grow food for animals
that we're going to eat.

00:14:36.390 --> 00:14:39.230
And you guys are engineers.

00:14:39.230 --> 00:14:40.284
You are thought leaders.

00:14:40.284 --> 00:14:41.200
Now, think about this.

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:44.820
If you had a pile of
grain on the table,

00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:46.905
and you could either
eat that yourself

00:14:46.905 --> 00:14:48.530
to get your protein
and your nutrition,

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:52.090
or you can give six times
that amount to an animal

00:14:52.090 --> 00:14:55.020
that you're trying to eat
so you can get it's flesh,

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:56.780
it's a really bad
exchange of energy.

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:00.130
But that's what we're
doing all over the planet.

00:15:00.130 --> 00:15:06.100
There's a really dangerous
myth that we need

00:15:06.100 --> 00:15:07.640
meat for human consumption.

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:09.690
We think, oh, to be
a man to be strong

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:11.907
you have to eat that way.

00:15:11.907 --> 00:15:12.990
You have to eat an animal.

00:15:12.990 --> 00:15:16.030
Well, in fact, the next
movie I'm working on

00:15:16.030 --> 00:15:17.630
is called "Game Change."

00:15:17.630 --> 00:15:20.770
It's being executive produced
by James and Suzy Cameron

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:22.260
from "Avatar."

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:25.500
And one of the
heroes in our movie

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:28.370
is a guy that won the-- this
is a documentary by the way.

00:15:28.370 --> 00:15:31.279
So he was an ultimate
fighting champion.

00:15:31.279 --> 00:15:32.070
And he got injured.

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:34.517
And he thought, well, what
can I do for nutrition?

00:15:34.517 --> 00:15:35.350
What's the best way?

00:15:35.350 --> 00:15:36.680
What can I eat to heal myself.

00:15:36.680 --> 00:15:38.740
And he found very little
information out there

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:40.850
and that most
doctors do 14 years

00:15:40.850 --> 00:15:45.570
of learning to be a
doctor, but not have

00:15:45.570 --> 00:15:48.270
a single hour in your
curriculum of nutrition.

00:15:50.850 --> 00:15:53.530
But he found out that
the gladiators, which

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:55.490
were the first ultimate
fighting champions,

00:15:55.490 --> 00:15:56.880
were actually vegans.

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:58.550
They didn't eat meat.

00:15:58.550 --> 00:16:00.620
These two professors
from Austria,

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:02.635
who we just interviewed
last month, went in.

00:16:02.635 --> 00:16:04.260
And they looked at
the strontium levels

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:05.400
in the teeth and the bones.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:07.450
And they could determine
that, in fact, they

00:16:07.450 --> 00:16:09.454
were not meat eaters.

00:16:09.454 --> 00:16:10.370
They were vegetarians.

00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:11.100
They were vegans.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:12.932
In fact, they were
called the barleymen.

00:16:12.932 --> 00:16:14.640
When they go back into
the documentation,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:16.710
they found that was
one of the concoctions

00:16:16.710 --> 00:16:18.200
that they ate for protein.

00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:20.360
It's a very recent
myth that you have

00:16:20.360 --> 00:16:22.220
to eat animals for
human consumption.

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:25.740
We've just been sold a bill
of goods about all this.

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:27.950
If you look at your teeth,
if you have cats or dogs,

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:30.010
go back and look
at their dentition.

00:16:30.010 --> 00:16:31.240
They're carnivores.

00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:33.770
But the back molars--
there's no back molars--

00:16:33.770 --> 00:16:36.630
but they have very pointy,
sharp teeth with serrations

00:16:36.630 --> 00:16:38.490
that are used for gulping meat.

00:16:38.490 --> 00:16:41.170
And it goes into a very
short digestive track.

00:16:41.170 --> 00:16:45.280
But we have incisors
here that are

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:48.490
used to crunch through an
avocado or a piece of fruit.

00:16:48.490 --> 00:16:50.780
And these molars
are used to crush

00:16:50.780 --> 00:16:53.040
beans, legumes, vegetables.

00:16:53.040 --> 00:16:55.030
We are omnivores.

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:56.860
But our gut tract
and our teeth is

00:16:56.860 --> 00:17:00.264
all about being a vegetarian.

00:17:00.264 --> 00:17:01.680
Sort of fast
forwarding into that,

00:17:01.680 --> 00:17:03.846
but we want to talk obviously
about extinction more.

00:17:03.846 --> 00:17:09.359
So the idea is how do you
scale up these issues?

00:17:09.359 --> 00:17:12.609
Look what we did with "The
Cove" with 23,000 dolphins down

00:17:12.609 --> 00:17:13.670
to 6,000.

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:15.859
And I think, OK, mass
extinction event.

00:17:15.859 --> 00:17:19.160
How do you get that film out
there and get people to see it.

00:17:19.160 --> 00:17:21.400
So I knew it was about scale.

00:17:21.400 --> 00:17:25.579
So we had the film at
Sundance this last year.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:28.849
And we licensed it to
the Discovery Channel.

00:17:28.849 --> 00:17:31.140
There's a reason we did it,
because they were paying us

00:17:31.140 --> 00:17:32.970
a lot of money
for a documentary.

00:17:32.970 --> 00:17:35.150
I was only-- still only
$0.30 on the dollar,

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:37.191
because you don't make a
lot of money when you do

00:17:37.191 --> 00:17:38.230
documentaries.

00:17:38.230 --> 00:17:40.230
But they promised us
a global audience.

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:42.620
And they put it out in 220
countries and territories

00:17:42.620 --> 00:17:44.070
on a single day.

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:46.820
And 36 million people
saw it the first weekend.

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:50.040
It's showing, again, I think
either tonight or tomorrow,

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:52.560
"Racing Extinction"
But 36 million

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:55.510
is a really good launch
for f documentary.

00:17:55.510 --> 00:18:00.410
But what you need to do
though is get it up to scale.

00:18:00.410 --> 00:18:04.510
It doesn't matter if 36
million people see it.

00:18:04.510 --> 00:18:08.530
What you need is
10% or up to 16.5%

00:18:08.530 --> 00:18:10.830
of the population to
see it before-- that's

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:13.510
the tipping point-- what Malcolm
Gladwell talks in his book

00:18:13.510 --> 00:18:14.010
about.

00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:16.814
But the science shows you
might need is a little as 10%

00:18:16.814 --> 00:18:19.230
of the people that have an
unwavering belief in the truth.

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:22.990
And then the rest of the
population falls like dominoes.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:29.520
And in "Racing Extinction," we
had premiered at the Tribeca

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:33.450
Film Festival-- I think it
was like the year before last

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:34.080
with this film.

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:37.095
And it was a rough cut-- the
Tribeca Film Festival where

00:18:37.095 --> 00:18:41.686
I just got back from 20 minutes
ago, is going on right now.

00:18:41.686 --> 00:18:43.060
But we did a rough
cut screening.

00:18:43.060 --> 00:18:44.875
And in that screening,
what we do is

00:18:44.875 --> 00:18:46.750
we are trying to alert
the world that there's

00:18:46.750 --> 00:18:48.400
a mass extinction going on.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:52.380
And Ban Ki-moon, who's the
Secretary General of the United

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:55.540
Nations, allowed us the day
before the big climate march

00:18:55.540 --> 00:18:58.080
in New York, allowed us to
use the building as these

00:18:58.080 --> 00:19:00.770
for these projections to give
endangered species a voice.

00:19:00.770 --> 00:19:04.530
We took the 39-story
Secretariat Building--

00:19:04.530 --> 00:19:07.900
used that for a big canvas and
then used the General Assembly

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:08.750
Building.

00:19:08.750 --> 00:19:10.790
It was five IMAX
screens together.

00:19:10.790 --> 00:19:15.600
We tiled about 16, 30,000-lumen
projectors together to do this

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:17.300
huge projection event.

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:20.380
But I'd always wanted-- That
was the same right before we

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:22.830
got here that I usually stay
at the Maritime Hotel right

00:19:22.830 --> 00:19:23.580
across the street.

00:19:23.580 --> 00:19:25.520
And Eric Goode,
who runs the hotel,

00:19:25.520 --> 00:19:27.490
saves endangered species,
loves the work we do,

00:19:27.490 --> 00:19:28.970
and he always gives me
the penthouse suite,

00:19:28.970 --> 00:19:31.020
which overlooks the
Empire State Building.

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:33.620
And I thought I want to light
up the Empire State Building

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:34.830
with endangered species.

00:19:34.830 --> 00:19:37.630
And we had a scene in there that
was Tony Malcolm, who owns it,

00:19:37.630 --> 00:19:39.890
is a good friend of mine.

00:19:39.890 --> 00:19:42.520
And he said, well, Louie, if
you can get permission to do it,

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:43.920
I'll let you use the building.

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:45.400
And I've been trying
for four years

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:49.390
to light up the building
since the last two years

00:19:49.390 --> 00:19:51.380
of the Bloomberg administration.

00:19:51.380 --> 00:19:59.470
And I was at an event
right before the COP21.

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:02.410
And there was 50
heads of organizations

00:20:02.410 --> 00:20:04.710
like the Sierra Club,
Greenpeace, myself,

00:20:04.710 --> 00:20:07.190
in the room over at Norman
and Lyn Lear's house.

00:20:07.190 --> 00:20:09.660
Norman Lear is the most
successful producer

00:20:09.660 --> 00:20:11.350
ever for television.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:15.430
And the first film I did, "The
Cove," was sold at their house.

00:20:15.430 --> 00:20:18.640
We couldn't sell it at Sundance
six years ago when we came out.

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:22.900
But in that room were two
people-- the head of Lionsgate

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:27.270
and Jeff Skoll from--
what's the company?

00:20:27.270 --> 00:20:27.990
What does he do?

00:20:27.990 --> 00:20:29.490
PayPal?

00:20:29.490 --> 00:20:30.340
Jeff Skoll.

00:20:30.340 --> 00:20:30.930
Help me out.

00:20:30.930 --> 00:20:33.240
You guys have to know who he is.

00:20:33.240 --> 00:20:35.120
Anyway, he was
Participant Media.

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:38.710
Anyway, Lionsgate
bought the film.

00:20:38.710 --> 00:20:40.370
Jeff Skoll that runs
Participant Media

00:20:40.370 --> 00:20:42.040
does outreach campaigns
for films like ours.

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:44.540
He said, if you buy the film,
I'll do the outreach campaign.

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:47.234
And so in that room, it was
a very powerful room to be.

00:20:47.234 --> 00:20:48.400
That made my life go around.

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:49.920
So five years later,
now I'm sitting

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:53.330
in this room with 50 of the
heads of these organizations

00:20:53.330 --> 00:20:55.870
and five the people down
below Ban Ki-moon working

00:20:55.870 --> 00:20:58.100
on the environment before COP21.

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:00.329
And Lyn says to
me, Louie, can you

00:21:00.329 --> 00:21:02.370
talk about your movie,
"Racing Extinction," which

00:21:02.370 --> 00:21:03.430
was over at that point.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:07.321
We had the ending
with the UN in it.

00:21:07.321 --> 00:21:09.570
And I said, well, I don't
want to talk about the movie

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:10.986
so much, but what
I've been trying

00:21:10.986 --> 00:21:15.440
to do to really end the movie
is to light up the Empire State

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:15.940
Building.

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:19.024
Does anybody in this room
know Bill de Blasio--

00:21:19.024 --> 00:21:19.940
the mayor of New York?

00:21:19.940 --> 00:21:22.880
And Norman Lear, who is
leaning up against the wall,

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:24.870
says, I know Bill.

00:21:24.870 --> 00:21:26.670
And he flies to New
York the next day.

00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:28.290
It was on a Saturday
at this house.

00:21:28.290 --> 00:21:30.250
And the next Wednesday,
I get an e-mail

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:32.510
from Bill de Blasio
saying, cool,

00:21:32.510 --> 00:21:34.020
how do we make this happen?

00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:36.740
And so right there, we
got the wheels in place

00:21:36.740 --> 00:21:38.560
to light up the
Empire State Building.

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:41.014
Now, the problem
was our distributor

00:21:41.014 --> 00:21:42.305
was like, you know what, Louie?

00:21:42.305 --> 00:21:43.800
The movie is good
enough the way it is.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:45.030
You don't need to touch it.

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:45.890
It's great.

00:21:45.890 --> 00:21:48.430
It was a wonderful,
global ending to the film.

00:21:48.430 --> 00:21:49.660
