even when its head is
chopped off and sitting

00:44:42.640 --> 00:44:45.460
on the slaughterhouse
floor and still smiling.

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:47.000
There have bigger brains.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:48.670
And they are more sentient.

00:44:48.670 --> 00:44:51.250
The neurons that are associated
with sentient neurons

00:44:51.250 --> 00:44:52.520
are more familial.

00:44:52.520 --> 00:44:55.930
They hang out in family pods
like orcas their entire life

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:57.540
with their mother.

00:44:57.540 --> 00:45:00.100
When you start to see a film
like that, that explains what

00:45:00.100 --> 00:45:02.490
the problem is,
it's like instead

00:45:02.490 --> 00:45:05.470
of trying to explain it
and spend an hour or two

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:07.970
at a lecture, now he's got
tens of millions of people

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:09.720
around the country,
around the world, that

00:45:09.720 --> 00:45:10.310
understand the problem.

00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:12.476
And it's just a matter going
from country to country

00:45:12.476 --> 00:45:14.090
to try to close these
businesses down.

00:45:14.090 --> 00:45:15.131
Same thing with the film.

00:45:15.131 --> 00:45:17.432
If you could get
the film out there--

00:45:17.432 --> 00:45:19.890
Discovery did a great job of
it getting the film out there.

00:45:19.890 --> 00:45:21.660
But we're still not
at that 10% level.

00:45:21.660 --> 00:45:25.080
36 million people
worldwide is not that big.

00:45:25.080 --> 00:45:28.240
We need to do that in America.

00:45:28.240 --> 00:45:29.850
So tell your friends
about the film.

00:45:32.485 --> 00:45:34.110
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
you for being here.

00:45:34.110 --> 00:45:35.740
And thanks for all
your great work.

00:45:35.740 --> 00:45:37.480
I think it's very
sobering statistics

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:39.750
that you're sharing
in that I think

00:45:39.750 --> 00:45:41.740
something like 50%
of greenhouse gases

00:45:41.740 --> 00:45:43.750
are produced by
animal agriculture.

00:45:43.750 --> 00:45:45.732
It's really terrible.

00:45:45.732 --> 00:45:47.940
So I really appreciate your
call to action for people

00:45:47.940 --> 00:45:50.860
to take up vegan
diets as one way

00:45:50.860 --> 00:45:53.170
to combat this thing
that's going on.

00:45:53.170 --> 00:45:54.700
My question is,
why do you think--

00:45:54.700 --> 00:45:56.960
and I watch very closely
the COP21 and now

00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:00.470
the US dietary guidelines, which
came out in 2015, both of which

00:46:00.470 --> 00:46:03.240
seem to completely ignore the
issue of animal agriculture.

00:46:03.240 --> 00:46:05.320
It wasn't even brought
up or mentioned.

00:46:05.320 --> 00:46:07.170
Sustainability wasn't
even an afterthought

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:08.700
for the dietary guidelines.

00:46:08.700 --> 00:46:11.480
So I'm wondering what
you think is the impetus

00:46:11.480 --> 00:46:13.910
to have our politicians
and leaders talking

00:46:13.910 --> 00:46:15.174
about these things openly?

00:46:15.174 --> 00:46:16.590
LOUIE PSIHOYOS:
Yeah, whenever you

00:46:16.590 --> 00:46:19.310
talk about dietary concerns,
you have the lobbyist

00:46:19.310 --> 00:46:23.240
go in really hard-- the
lobbyist go to the politicians

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:26.830
to try to get the
language dumbed down.

00:46:26.830 --> 00:46:30.170
I remember when the guidelines
came out five or six years ago

00:46:30.170 --> 00:46:32.650
about, OK, eggs, dairy.

00:46:32.650 --> 00:46:33.800
It's a real problem.

00:46:33.800 --> 00:46:37.270
Milk should not be on
the food pyramid at all.

00:46:37.270 --> 00:46:40.610
This got crucified.

00:46:40.610 --> 00:46:45.290
It was too big of a
problem politically.

00:46:45.290 --> 00:46:46.950
The information is still there.

00:46:46.950 --> 00:46:52.070
The UN came out with the
guidelines for agriculture.

00:46:52.070 --> 00:46:54.770
And it's called the long
shadow of agriculture.

00:46:54.770 --> 00:46:58.230
And it said, we have to
reduce our consumption.

00:46:58.230 --> 00:47:03.510
The 50%, if you
look at-- I think

00:47:03.510 --> 00:47:07.860
it's 14.5% equivalent
of tailpipe emissions.

00:47:07.860 --> 00:47:11.020
So the consuming of meat
in America for consumption

00:47:11.020 --> 00:47:13.860
is more than that of all
the tailpipe emissions

00:47:13.860 --> 00:47:17.530
of all the industries that burn
fossil fuels-- planes, trains,

00:47:17.530 --> 00:47:19.180
automobiles.

00:47:19.180 --> 00:47:21.460
That's for certain--
at least 14.5%.

00:47:21.460 --> 00:47:23.490
50% is probably aggressive.

00:47:23.490 --> 00:47:25.610
But the thing is
we know that this

00:47:25.610 --> 00:47:29.080
is the one thing we can do right
away to turn the dials down.

00:47:29.080 --> 00:47:34.160
But this is an area where
we have to do it internally.

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:39.560
We showed the film in Bogota,
Colombia several months ago.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:42.480
And the day after--
this is a pretty heavy

00:47:42.480 --> 00:47:47.800
meat-eating country-- the day
after the students got together

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:49.560
and met with the chancellor.

00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:53.560
And he agreed to put
more of a vegan menu

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:55.970
with the several
thousand students there.

00:47:55.970 --> 00:47:57.850
And this is the kind
of change we need.

00:47:57.850 --> 00:48:00.730
We know that in
America, we don't work

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:02.040
on a national level as much.

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:04.740
I've testified against Sea
World for another film.

00:48:04.740 --> 00:48:06.830
But what we're
doing statewide is

00:48:06.830 --> 00:48:11.020
you could have a container
load of shark fins

00:48:11.020 --> 00:48:14.760
that are legal to possess,
sell, or distribute

00:48:14.760 --> 00:48:16.710
any way in Washington State.

00:48:16.710 --> 00:48:19.600
But that container
is not open if you

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.960
go on to Oregon, or
Idaho, or somewhere else,

00:48:22.960 --> 00:48:25.540
transport by truck
and get disseminated.

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:27.800
And US customs
officials say, there's

00:48:27.800 --> 00:48:28.970
nothing we can do about it.

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:33.030
We just made it illegal to
import it into the docks.

00:48:33.030 --> 00:48:37.316
And we're doing that in
California and in Oregon.

00:48:37.316 --> 00:48:38.690
Texas is the first
southern state

00:48:38.690 --> 00:48:40.270
that we have to
implement the law.

00:48:40.270 --> 00:48:43.320
So we're working
with legislations,

00:48:43.320 --> 00:48:45.550
but on a state-wide
basis like the same way

00:48:45.550 --> 00:48:50.207
that Warren Buffet does it with
his minions-- those bastards.

00:48:50.207 --> 00:48:51.790
And we're trying to
close them down so

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:55.750
we can take-- Seattle was the
third largest port in America.

00:48:55.750 --> 00:48:58.880
And this is making it very,
very difficult to-- in fact,

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:00.170
it wasn't just shark fins.

00:49:00.170 --> 00:49:08.600
There was ivory, rhino
horns, penguin-- 10 species.

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:10.060
So we can do it.

00:49:10.650 --> 00:49:13.814
It doesn't take much to get
a referendum these days.

00:49:13.814 --> 00:49:15.230
People talk about
these petitions.

00:49:15.230 --> 00:49:16.313
And they get all the time.

00:49:16.313 --> 00:49:17.620
People say, they don't work.

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:20.140
We killed SeaWorld
with petitions.

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:22.500
We got Willie Nelson,
Bare Naked Ladies--

00:49:22.500 --> 00:49:28.130
these 10 musical acts out of 12,
to stop performing at SeaWorld.

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:30.530
Richard Bloom, who is a
representative from the state I

00:49:30.530 --> 00:49:32.700
live in now, California,
came out with a law

00:49:32.700 --> 00:49:34.597
that it was just a first salvo.

00:49:34.597 --> 00:49:35.430
It was just an idea.

00:49:35.430 --> 00:49:39.520
The law was that he was going
to stop the breeding of dolphins

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:41.000
in California.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:42.864
That law, coupled
with my organization--

00:49:42.864 --> 00:49:44.780
I run the Oceanic
Preservation Society-- there

00:49:44.780 --> 00:49:45.880
were six people.

00:49:45.880 --> 00:49:47.670
We bought copies
of "Blackfish"--

00:49:47.670 --> 00:49:50.400
another film about
dolphins and orcas.

00:49:50.400 --> 00:49:53.170
We bought copies of
"Blackfish" and "The Cove."

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:56.350
And we gave them to all
the shareholders of the 10

00:49:56.350 --> 00:49:57.850
major investment of SeaWorld.

00:49:57.850 --> 00:50:00.510
That coupled with Richard
Bloom's proposed law

00:50:00.510 --> 00:50:02.614
caused the stock to
crash a billion dollars

00:50:02.614 --> 00:50:03.280
in a single day.

00:50:03.280 --> 00:50:05.717
And they haven't
recovered since.

00:50:05.717 --> 00:50:07.050
It wasn't just our organization.

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:08.300
We worked with
other organizations.

00:50:08.300 --> 00:50:09.800
That was a great
movie, "Blackfish."

00:50:09.800 --> 00:50:14.140
But together, we can
do incredible things.

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:17.740
We're trying to get
it illegal to bring

00:50:17.740 --> 00:50:20.410
animal parts, body
parts, for trophies

00:50:20.410 --> 00:50:22.480
from Africa to America.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:27.030
And UPS buckled with 167,000
members on the petition.

00:50:27.030 --> 00:50:30.520
We're working right now
this week today with FedEx

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:32.430
to do the same thing.

00:50:32.430 --> 00:50:35.820
We showed that we could
legally transport shark fins

00:50:35.820 --> 00:50:38.820
to states using their system.

00:50:38.820 --> 00:50:40.420
And we did it.

00:50:40.420 --> 00:50:41.950
We photographed it.

00:50:41.950 --> 00:50:45.440
There are people from
Federal Express complicit

00:50:45.440 --> 00:50:49.710
with showing us how we could
avoid federal law by shipping

00:50:49.710 --> 00:50:50.670
with them.

00:50:50.670 --> 00:50:54.330
And so that is with their
head of marketing right now.

00:50:54.330 --> 00:50:57.220
We will release it
probably today or tomorrow.

00:50:57.220 --> 00:51:02.100
And if they don't buckle,
we'll go public with it

00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:04.370
and start a petition.

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:07.960
So a 160,000
petitions is nothing

00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:11.390
to get these companies
to change law.

00:51:11.390 --> 00:51:17.090
All it takes is getting people
together-- getting people

00:51:17.090 --> 00:51:21.610
to understand that taking the
15 seconds to 5 seconds it

00:51:21.610 --> 00:51:26.382
takes to sign a petition
really helps-- sign and share.

00:51:26.382 --> 00:51:28.590
AUDIENCE: So going back to
my question, who would you

00:51:28.590 --> 00:51:32.470
petition and how to create 100
million vegans in the United

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:34.580
States tomorrow?

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:36.390
LOUIE PSIHOYOS: I'm
working on a film--

00:51:36.390 --> 00:51:39.040
the one I'm working with
James and Suzy Cameron.

00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:39.990
We're working on that.

00:51:39.990 --> 00:51:41.698
We're trying to get
Arnold Schwarzenegger

00:51:41.698 --> 00:51:46.470
as an executive
producer as well.

00:51:46.470 --> 00:51:48.380
Li Ka-shing, the
richest guy in Asia--

00:51:48.380 --> 00:51:50.020
he's also an executive producer.

00:51:50.020 --> 00:51:51.550
We'll get the film out there.

00:51:51.550 --> 00:51:55.050
I work on that issue
every day with the idea

00:51:55.050 --> 00:51:57.800
that it doesn't
happen overnight.

00:51:57.800 --> 00:51:59.530
It's going to happen
with this film.

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:01.270
We want to get the
film distributed.

00:52:01.270 --> 00:52:05.020
And then, at some point,
maybe release it for free.

00:52:05.020 --> 00:52:07.515
The problem with people like
in the environmental movement.

00:52:07.515 --> 00:52:09.390
They say, well, all your
care about is money.

00:52:09.390 --> 00:52:10.514
You got to release it free.

00:52:10.514 --> 00:52:13.520
It's really expensive to release
movies. "Racing Extinction" was

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:15.150
an $8 million, $9 million movie.

00:52:15.150 --> 00:52:17.060
We sold it for $3 million.

00:52:17.060 --> 00:52:18.560
I probably can't
tell those figures.

00:52:18.560 --> 00:52:19.810
Just cut that from the record.

00:52:22.530 --> 00:52:25.810
But it's an expensive
movie to give away.

00:52:25.810 --> 00:52:26.950
I sold my house.

00:52:26.950 --> 00:52:29.330
And I got $700,000
of my own money.

00:52:29.330 --> 00:52:30.200
I'm not a rich guy.

00:52:30.200 --> 00:52:31.939
Everything I own
is in that film.

00:52:31.939 --> 00:52:33.730
And people say, why
don't you give it away?

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:34.810
It's like, you know what?

00:52:34.810 --> 00:52:35.590
I've got to eat.

00:52:35.590 --> 00:52:38.120
I've got insurance to pay.

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:40.446
If I run a Google
on the laptop, I've

00:52:40.446 --> 00:52:41.570
got to pay for that laptop.

00:52:41.570 --> 00:52:43.730
They're not giving
it away to me.

00:52:43.730 --> 00:52:44.710
Life is expensive.

00:52:44.710 --> 00:52:47.030
And I got crews that
need to get paid.

00:52:47.030 --> 00:52:49.690
It's like you can't
give away art just

00:52:49.690 --> 00:52:53.640
because it's well-intentioned.

00:52:53.640 --> 00:52:57.940
And sometimes we have investors
that need to get paid.

00:52:57.940 --> 00:52:59.820
But there is a scale.

00:52:59.820 --> 00:53:03.772
We are very conscious that we
want to hit that 10% to 16.5%

00:53:03.772 --> 00:53:05.105
number no matter how it happens.

00:53:10.450 --> 00:53:12.474
We had a deal to sell
"The Cove" in China.

00:53:12.474 --> 00:53:13.973
And somebody said,
oh, they are only

00:53:13.973 --> 00:53:15.580
going to offer you $30,000.

00:53:15.580 --> 00:53:16.440
Fine.

00:53:16.440 --> 00:53:20.150
They are going to reach a half
a billion people in China.

00:53:20.150 --> 00:53:21.320
We didn't do it.

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:24.860
And I can remember we went
to China about a year later.

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:27.590
And people that
were with my team

00:53:27.590 --> 00:53:29.340
were signing autographs
on the street.

00:53:29.340 --> 00:53:31.570
They recognize them
from the movie.

00:53:31.570 --> 00:53:34.360
Somebody had pirated the movie
in Cantonese and Mandarin.

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:37.840
And it was like every school
kid of 15 to 25 years old

00:53:37.840 --> 00:53:38.930
had seen "The Cove."

00:53:38.930 --> 00:53:40.910
And now they are
celebrities on the streets.

00:53:40.910 --> 00:53:43.650
But it's because it went viral,
because we didn't sell it.

00:53:43.650 --> 00:53:48.230
Somebody has took it under the--
let's just-- I like this movie.

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:49.250
Let's just rip it.

00:53:49.250 --> 00:53:52.560
And it went viral.

00:53:52.560 --> 00:53:56.390
But for me, at some point,
I don't care about the money

00:53:56.390 --> 00:53:56.960
so much.

00:53:56.960 --> 00:54:00.710
I just want to get it out
there and solve the issue so we

00:54:00.710 --> 00:54:01.910
can go on to something else.

00:54:01.910 --> 00:54:04.170
There always has to be
another problem to solve.

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:05.034
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:05.034 --> 00:54:06.950
FEMALE SPEAKER: Are there
any other questions?

00:54:09.950 --> 00:54:12.810
All right, got one over there?

00:54:12.810 --> 00:54:15.310
I think this will be
probably the last one.

00:54:15.310 --> 00:54:16.560
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:19.970
Thanks for being here.

00:54:19.970 --> 00:54:25.420
You were on to covering China
for "Racing Extinction."

00:54:25.420 --> 00:54:29.170
Could you tell us about maybe
the most horrifying moment

00:54:29.170 --> 00:54:30.939
that you experienced there?

00:54:30.939 --> 00:54:31.980
LOUIE PSIHOYOS: In China?

00:54:31.980 --> 00:54:33.100
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:33.810
Or Hong Kong.

00:54:33.810 --> 00:54:35.100
LOUIE PSIHOYOS: Or Hong Kong.

00:54:35.100 --> 00:54:37.720
Actually, we were in Guangzhou.

00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:40.710
And they had the illegal
wildlife markets there.

00:54:40.710 --> 00:54:43.390
And they had been
shutdown twice that year.

00:54:43.390 --> 00:54:44.350
And it keeps on moving.

00:54:44.350 --> 00:54:46.391
There's so much demand,
it keeps on springing up,

00:54:46.391 --> 00:54:47.977
even though people face jail.

00:54:47.977 --> 00:54:49.810
So you go there at like
3:00 in the morning,

00:54:49.810 --> 00:54:52.110
and people are selling
just about everything

00:54:52.110 --> 00:54:54.180
you can imagine-- a
lot of illegal wildlife

00:54:54.180 --> 00:54:56.720
or a lot of wildlife that
we wouldn't eat in America.

00:54:56.720 --> 00:54:58.670
But just the same--
just the screams

00:54:58.670 --> 00:55:02.360
and the horrors of these
animals being put into cages

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:06.260
or being killed, because this--
blocks and blocks and blocks.

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:08.320
It would be like the
Meat District here--

00:55:08.320 --> 00:55:09.860
like imagine every shop.

00:55:09.860 --> 00:55:11.650
Like you go to the
Chelsea Market.

00:55:11.650 --> 00:55:14.540
And there is 15
of them that size.

00:55:14.540 --> 00:55:17.910
And they are all selling
endangered snakes,

00:55:17.910 --> 00:55:21.250
endangered birds, all
kinds of farm animals,

00:55:21.250 --> 00:55:24.080
but things that I
don't know dogs,

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:26.092
cats, rats-- they're
all being eaten.

00:55:26.092 --> 00:55:27.550
And it was like
everything that had

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:30.270
a heartbeat, including
insects and larvae,

00:55:30.270 --> 00:55:31.260
was being sold there.

00:55:31.260 --> 00:55:36.420
And there was something
really disturbing about that.

00:55:36.420 --> 00:55:38.320
It was done so openly.

00:55:38.320 --> 00:55:41.380
And you know what?

00:55:41.380 --> 00:55:43.924
In 1986, I was doing a
story for "Fortune Magazine"

00:55:43.924 --> 00:55:45.340
on the biggest
independently owned

00:55:45.340 --> 00:55:46.560
cattle ranches in America.

00:55:46.560 --> 00:55:48.440
And I went to one that
was so big in Oklahoma

00:55:48.440 --> 00:55:50.260
that they had their
own slaughter house.

00:55:50.260 --> 00:55:53.897
And that convinced me to
become-- I wasn't a vegetarian.

00:55:53.897 --> 00:55:54.730
I was a pescatarian.

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:57.280
But I stopped eating things
that walked right then

00:55:57.280 --> 00:55:59.934
and haven't since.

00:55:59.934 --> 00:56:01.350
When they kill
these animals, they

00:56:01.350 --> 00:56:02.840
put a cap bolt to the skull.

00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:04.465
It was supposed to
kill them instantly.

00:56:04.465 --> 00:56:05.640
But it's an assembly line.

00:56:05.640 --> 00:56:10.627
They did 500 a day-- 500 cows
a day in this small facility.

00:56:10.627 --> 00:56:11.710
And they rip the skin off.

00:56:11.710 --> 00:56:13.070
And they hang it upside down.

00:56:13.070 --> 00:56:16.050
And it's supposed to be dead, as
people are shaving parts of it

00:56:16.050 --> 00:56:18.370
off and putting it into
different bins and stuff.

00:56:18.370 --> 00:56:21.566
And I remember this cow
was hanging upside down.

00:56:21.566 --> 00:56:22.690
it was supposed to be dead.

00:56:22.690 --> 00:56:25.160
And it was looking at
me and following me

00:56:25.160 --> 00:56:27.150
as it went around in
this conveyor belt.

00:56:27.150 --> 00:56:28.229
And it was still alive.

00:56:28.229 --> 00:56:29.520
Part of it was still conscious.

00:56:29.520 --> 00:56:32.170
And I thought at that point,
I don't want to be part of it.

00:56:32.170 --> 00:56:33.600
Now, I made a conscious effort.

00:56:33.600 --> 00:56:38.510
But when you see the scale that
was being done, it was amazing.

00:56:38.510 --> 00:56:41.560
There was a rooftop in
Hong Kong that we went to.

00:56:41.560 --> 00:56:46.230
And it was seven pallets
deep of shark fins.

00:56:46.230 --> 00:56:49.000
And it was spread out all over
this roof overlooking Hong Kong

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:50.050
Harbor.

00:56:50.050 --> 00:56:53.210
And you each shark
has seven fins to it.

00:56:53.210 --> 00:56:56.315
And you see these
little baby ones.

00:56:56.315 --> 00:56:58.480
I've dove all over the world.

00:56:58.480 --> 00:57:00.872
And every time you
go back to a place,

00:57:00.872 --> 00:57:02.080
you see less and less sharks.

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:04.080
And it was because of the
demand for shark fins.

00:57:04.080 --> 00:57:06.409
Now, if you haven't seen
"The Cove," or sorry,

00:57:06.409 --> 00:57:07.950
"Racing Extinction,"
what you realize

00:57:07.950 --> 00:57:10.850
is that one of the
guys in our film

00:57:10.850 --> 00:57:15.080
had photographed
a live shark fin.

00:57:15.080 --> 00:57:16.930
What they do is a
lot of the sharks,

00:57:16.930 --> 00:57:19.090
they just cut off the fins
and throw the shark back

00:57:19.090 --> 00:57:24.180
to die, basically with all
its appendages cut off.

00:57:24.180 --> 00:57:26.690
And the shark needs-- it
doesn't grow them back.

00:57:26.690 --> 00:57:32.570
It needs to swim to breathe--
water rushing by its gills.

00:57:32.570 --> 00:57:34.880
So these animals are left
to die on the bottom.

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:37.510
And one of the guys in
our movie had filmed this.

00:57:37.510 --> 00:57:42.200
That film went viral
in China with a PSA

00:57:42.200 --> 00:57:44.260
that Yao Ming, the
basketball player, did.

00:57:44.260 --> 00:57:46.650
And the airing of
that film was seen

00:57:46.650 --> 00:57:48.500
by more than a billion
people in Asia.

00:57:48.500 --> 00:57:52.100
And that, along with
the legislation,

00:57:52.100 --> 00:57:57.230
it's now illegal to serve shark
fin at banquets at government

00:57:57.230 --> 00:57:59.290
banquets in China.

00:57:59.290 --> 00:58:03.410
That one PSA helped reduce
the demand for shark fin soup

00:58:03.410 --> 00:58:04.950
by 70%.

00:58:04.950 --> 00:58:06.130
That's the power of imagery.

00:58:06.130 --> 00:58:08.754
That's one of the themes running
through "Racing Extinction" is

00:58:08.754 --> 00:58:10.436
that imagery is very powerful.

00:58:10.436 --> 00:58:11.560
And that's why we do films.

00:58:11.560 --> 00:58:12.893
That's why I was a photographer.

00:58:12.893 --> 00:58:17.160
I was like, I did it to
try to change the world.

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:20.270
That's why I was
working-- the first story

00:58:20.270 --> 00:58:22.910
I did for "National Geographic"
was a story on garbage

00:58:22.910 --> 00:58:24.170
and recycling.

00:58:24.170 --> 00:58:25.600
I started in 1981.

00:58:25.600 --> 00:58:27.970
And people weren't talking
about recycling back then.

00:58:27.970 --> 00:58:31.010
Now, there's recycling
in my hotel room.

00:58:31.010 --> 00:58:32.570
But I was on the
vanguard of people.

00:58:32.570 --> 00:58:36.960
But at "Geographic," when
we came out with that story,

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:40.422
we had 15 million people saw
the magazine at that point.

00:58:40.422 --> 00:58:42.380
It was the second biggest
subscription magazine

00:58:42.380 --> 00:58:43.390
in the world.

00:58:43.390 --> 00:58:47.290
And it had a pass around rate
of about three to four people

00:58:47.290 --> 00:58:48.290
would see each magazine.

00:58:48.290 --> 00:58:51.060
So you could hit that
Malcolm Gladwell number--

00:58:51.060 --> 00:58:55.910
that magic 15%-- just by virtue
of getting one article out

00:58:55.910 --> 00:58:57.350
there that people see.

00:58:57.350 --> 00:58:59.100
I am not saying that
50% of the population

00:58:59.100 --> 00:59:00.970
became recyclers overnight.

00:59:00.970 --> 00:59:04.120
But it became that first salvo.

00:59:04.120 --> 00:59:05.680
The research shows
that if you want

00:59:05.680 --> 00:59:08.880
to get a movie scene
in America, people

00:59:08.880 --> 00:59:11.400
need to hear it six or seven
times before they'll actually

00:59:11.400 --> 00:59:11.900
go see it.

00:59:11.900 --> 00:59:16.160
So that means it has to
have a strong word of mouth.

00:59:16.160 --> 00:59:18.880
The celebrity that's associated
with the movie on the cover

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:20.350
of a magazine that you adore.

00:59:20.350 --> 00:59:22.460
You see bus stop
ads, and billboards,

00:59:22.460 --> 00:59:26.940
and they blow it out
there-- $250 million movie--

00:59:26.940 --> 00:59:29.544
will have $100 million
, $150 million.

00:59:29.544 --> 00:59:31.960
If it's really a bomb, they
will throw another $50 million

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:33.590
to $100 million at
it, because they

00:59:33.590 --> 00:59:35.140
know if they don't hit those
numbers the first weekend

00:59:35.140 --> 00:59:37.556
or two before people figure
out that it's a piece of crap,

00:59:37.556 --> 00:59:40.590
they won't see it.

00:59:40.590 --> 00:59:43.370
As documentary filmmakers,
we don't have that.

00:59:43.370 --> 00:59:45.280
But what we do is
we have good ideas.

00:59:45.280 --> 00:59:50.900
We could light up the UN,
the Empire State Building,

00:59:50.900 --> 00:59:51.880
or the Vatican.

00:59:51.880 --> 00:59:53.280
I wish that was my idea.

00:59:53.280 --> 00:59:55.160
But what we're
doing now is saying,

00:59:55.160 --> 00:59:57.030
OK, the film is out there.

00:59:57.030 --> 01:00:01.560
But we still work on cove
issues six years later.

01:00:01.560 --> 01:00:04.044
Recently, SeaWorld just
because of all the pressure

01:00:04.044 --> 01:00:06.210
we put on it, they announced
that they weren't going

01:00:06.210 --> 01:00:07.890
to do captive breeding anymore.

01:00:07.890 --> 01:00:11.180
They're stopping all
their orca programs.

01:00:11.180 --> 01:00:14.530
And that's because of
"Blackfish," "The Cove."

01:00:14.530 --> 01:00:18.090
The executive producer
of "Blackfish"

01:00:18.090 --> 01:00:21.280
was inspired to become a
vegan by seeing "The Cove."

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:25.510
And she's never done a movie
before because of "The Cove,"

01:00:25.510 --> 01:00:29.090
because she put the money
into "Blackfish." so there's

01:00:29.090 --> 01:00:32.480
like a reciprocal effect of
doing one good thing that

01:00:32.480 --> 01:00:34.020
can really go viral.

01:00:36.865 --> 01:00:38.450
And I worked for
"National Geographic"

01:00:38.450 --> 01:00:39.866
over the course
of about 18 years.

01:00:39.866 --> 01:00:42.330
I did, I don't know,
13, 14 stories for them.

01:00:45.290 --> 01:00:47.510
I can remember one time
watching somebody actually

01:00:47.510 --> 01:00:51.570
see my movie-- my
story on a plane.

01:00:51.570 --> 01:00:52.966
And he flipped through that.

01:00:52.966 --> 01:00:54.840
It took me a year and
a half to do the story.

01:00:54.840 --> 01:00:56.870
He flipped through
it as fast as you

01:00:56.870 --> 01:00:58.175
could flip through a magazine.

01:00:58.175 --> 01:00:59.050
It was heartbreaking.

01:00:59.050 --> 01:01:01.990
But with a film,
you got 90 minutes

01:01:01.990 --> 01:01:03.760
to change people's hearts.

01:01:03.760 --> 01:01:06.010
And that's an extraordinary
amount of time these days.

01:01:06.010 --> 01:01:07.910
You guys probably
know more than I do.

01:01:07.910 --> 01:01:11.780
People say that people
don't more than a couple--

01:01:11.780 --> 01:01:14.080
you can't have a YouTube
that's going to last

01:01:14.080 --> 01:01:15.559
more than a couple minutes.

01:01:15.559 --> 01:01:16.100
I don't know.

01:01:16.100 --> 01:01:21.550
I think people have a propensity
to-- I binge watch "House

01:01:21.550 --> 01:01:23.390
of Cards" when it comes out.

01:01:23.390 --> 01:01:24.780
I'll do it one weekend.

01:01:24.780 --> 01:01:26.520
I think if you have
a good story to tell,

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:29.130
people will endure
just about anything.

01:01:29.130 --> 01:01:31.210
The trick that you have
with environmentalists

01:01:31.210 --> 01:01:32.960
is how do you make a good story?

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:35.200
What we try to do is we
try to make a story that

01:01:35.200 --> 01:01:37.400
is really entertaining.

01:01:37.400 --> 01:01:39.944
"Rolling Stone" said
that, like I said,

01:01:39.944 --> 01:01:42.110
"The Cove" was a cross
between the "Bourne Identity"

01:01:42.110 --> 01:01:45.250
and "Flipper." "Racing
Extinction" is really

01:01:45.250 --> 01:01:47.780
the result of me watching too
many Jacques Cousteau specials

01:01:47.780 --> 01:01:49.730
and James Bond movies as a kid.

01:01:49.730 --> 01:01:51.720
We have a Tesla
that we tricked out.

01:01:51.720 --> 01:01:53.480
We wanted to make this Bond car.

01:01:53.480 --> 01:01:56.200
So we have a
luminescent paint job.

01:01:56.200 --> 01:01:58.509
We use it for getaways.

01:01:58.509 --> 01:02:00.050
We have a disappearing
license plate.

01:02:00.050 --> 01:02:01.466
We have a
forward-looking infrared

01:02:01.466 --> 01:02:03.240
that comes out of
the front on a Gimbal

01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:04.990
so we can see carbon
dioxide in real time.

01:02:04.990 --> 01:02:07.670
We have a 16,000-lumen projector
that comes out of the back with

01:02:07.670 --> 01:02:10.300
a hatch on a robotic arm so we
can project it on skyscrapers

01:02:10.300 --> 01:02:12.236
in real time.

01:02:12.236 --> 01:02:15.260
The car is freaking amazing.

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:20.300
But we knew that we had to
have some sort of hook in there

01:02:20.300 --> 01:02:23.730
so that if a kid of a
certain age saw the film,

01:02:23.730 --> 01:02:25.930
they would say you got to
at least go see the car.

01:02:28.820 --> 01:02:31.710
They may not understand--
they will get the exposition.

01:02:31.710 --> 01:02:34.520
They will get the story on
the way to seeing the car.

01:02:34.520 --> 01:02:36.400
But there all sorts of
interesting characters

01:02:36.400 --> 01:02:40.100
in this film that hopefully
hook people into the film.

01:02:40.100 --> 01:02:42.950
There's a lot going on in this
one little 90-minute sequence.

01:02:42.950 --> 01:02:44.670
But 90 minutes is
that enough time

01:02:44.670 --> 01:02:46.590
to actually change the DNA.

01:02:46.590 --> 01:02:48.250
Somebody should do
some research on it.

01:02:48.250 --> 01:02:55.110
But I think that we used to
read books and get changed.

01:02:55.110 --> 01:02:56.950
We're not reading
books en masse anymore.

01:02:56.950 --> 01:02:58.410
But we're watching films.

01:02:58.410 --> 01:03:02.280
And we're watching episodic
television by the buckets full.

01:03:02.280 --> 01:03:04.912
But if you can make a film
that changes people's hearts,

01:03:04.912 --> 01:03:06.120
we can change their behavior.

01:03:06.120 --> 01:03:08.258
I know that.

